14 (As enacted by Section 1 of this Act)
15 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
16 That Section(s) 7–14A–02 through 7–14A–09 of Article – Education of the Annotated Code
17 of Maryland be renumbered to be Section(s) 7–14A–03 through 7–14A–10, respectively.
18 SECTION 1. 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY
19 OF MARYLAND, That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
20 Article – Education
21 7–14A–01.
22 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
23 (c) “Prolonged state of emergency” means a state of emergency declared by the
24 [Governor under Title 14 of the Public Safety Article] STATE SUPERINTENDENT UNDER
25 § 7–14A–02 OF THIS SUBTITLE that prevents regular, in–person attendance at a public
26 school for at least 14 consecutive school days.
27 (e) “Virtual education” means academic instruction:
28 (1) In which one or more technologies are used to deliver a significant
29 portion of the teaching to students entirely or primarily online; and
30 (2) In which students and instructors participate remotely from separate
31 locations.
32 7–14A–02.

HOUSE BILL 288 3
1 (A) ON WRITTEN REQUEST OF A COUNTY SUPERINTENDENT OR A
2 DETERMINATION BY THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT THAT IMMEDIATE ACTION IS
3 NECESSARY, THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT MAY DECLARE A PROLONGED STATE OF
4 EMERGENCY THAT PREVENTS REGULAR, IN–PERSON ATTENDANCE AT A PUBLIC
5 SCHOOL FOR AT LEAST 14 CONSECUTIVE SCHOOL DAYS DUE TO:
6 (1) A NATURAL DISASTER;
7 (2) A CIVIL DISASTER;
8 (3) A PUBLIC HEALTH EMERGENCY; OR
9 (4) A SPECIFIC SECURITY THREAT IDENTIFIED BY FEDERAL, STATE,
10 OR LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT.
11 (B) IN MAKING A DECLARATION OF A PROLONGED STATE OF EMERGENCY
12 UNDER THIS SECTION, THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT SHALL:
13 (1) CONSULT THE GOVERNOR, AND IF APPROPRIATE:
14 (I) THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY
15 MANAGEMENT;
16 (II) THE DEPARTMENT OF STATE POLICE; OR
17 (III) THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH;
18 (2) ISSUE THE DECLARATION IN WRITING;
19 (3) INDICATE IN THE DECLARATION:
20 (I) THE NATURE OF THE EMERGENCY; AND
21 (II) THE SPECIFIC LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS OR INDIVIDUAL
22 SCHOOLS THREATENED OR AFFECTED, UNLESS THE EMERGENCY IS STATEWIDE IN
23 NATURE; AND
24 (4) DISSEMINATE THE DECLARATION PROMPTLY BY MEANS
25 CALCULATED TO PUBLICIZE THE CONTENTS OF THE DECLARATION.
26 (C) IF AN EMERGENCY THREATENS OR AFFECTS A PARTICULAR SCHOOL
27 WITHIN A LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM, THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT MAY DECLARE A
28 PROLONGED STATE OF EMERGENCY FOR THAT SCHOOL.

4 HOUSE BILL 288
1 (D) (1) A PROLONGED STATE OF EMERGENCY DECLARED IN
2 ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION MAY BE TERMINATED BY:
3 (I) A JOINT RESOLUTION BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY;
4 (II) AN AFFIRMATIVE VOTE BY THE STATE BOARD; OR
5 (III) A DECISION BY THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT.
6 (2) IF A PROLONGED STATE OF EMERGENCY IS TERMINATED BY ANY
7 METHOD LISTED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE STATE
8 SUPERINTENDENT SHALL ISSUE A DECLARATION DISSEMINATED PROMPTLY BY
9 MEANS CALCULATED TO PUBLICIZE THE TERMINATION OF THE PROLONGED STATE
10 OF EMERGENCY.
11 (E) NOTHING IN THIS SUBTITLE MAY BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT OR
12 INTERFERE WITH THE RESPONSIBILITIES OF THE SECRETARY OF HEALTH UNDER
13 TITLE 18 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE IN THE EVENT OF A PUBLIC HEALTH
14 EMERGENCY.
15 7–14A–02. 7–14A–03.
16 (a) If there is a prolonged state of emergency AFFECTING THE LOCAL SCHOOL
17 SYSTEM, a county board may transition the ONE OR MORE public schools in the county to
18 virtual education under an approved virtual education plan, subject to the limitations of
19 this section.
20 (b) (1) (i) On or before June 1, 2024, a county board shall, in consultation
21 with county administrators and school staff, adopt a virtual education plan for use during
22 a prolonged state of emergency AFFECTING THE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM.
23 (ii) A county board shall use the county board’s continuity of learning
24 plan in effect during the 2020–2021 school year to form a virtual education plan.
25 (2) A virtual education plan shall include the following components:
26 (i) A staffing and personnel assignment plan;
27 (ii) A student instruction plan;
28 (iii) A student assessment and learning support plan;
29 (iv) A social and emotional learning plan;
30 (v) A community communications plan;

HOUSE BILL 288 5
1 (vi) A technology plan;
2 (vii) A nutritional and health services plan; and
3 (viii) A plan for return to in–person instruction.
4 (c) A county board shall update the virtual education plan every 2 years.
5 (d) (1) If a prolonged state of emergency AFFECTING THE LOCAL SCHOOL
6 SYSTEM requires the cessation of in–school attendance at a public school and the county
7 board determines virtual education is required, a county board immediately shall
8 implement the virtual education plan and transition the public school to virtual education.
9 (2) (i) A county board may adjust the virtual education plan to fit the
10 specific needs of the schools affected and the specific circumstances of the emergency.
11 (ii) A county board shall submit an adjusted plan to the State Board
12 as soon as practicable.
13 (e) (1) Within 10 calendar days of receipt of a virtual education plan, the State
14 Board shall:
15 (i) Accept the plan; or
16 (ii) Return the plan to the county board for specific modification.
17 (2) If an adjusted virtual education plan is returned, the county board shall
18 modify and resubmit the plan within 5 calendar days after the date the plan is returned.
19 (f) The county board shall publish the most recent version of the virtual
20 education plan on the county board’s website.
21 (G) NOTHING IN THIS SUBTITLE MAY BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT OR
22 INTERFERE WITH THE RESPONSIBILITIES OF THE SECRETARY OF HEALTH UNDER
23 TITLE 18 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE IN THE EVENT OF A PUBLIC HEALTH
24 EMERGENCY.
25 7–14A–10.
26 The State Board shall adopt regulations to carry out the provisions of this subtitle,
27 including establishing minimum criteria for the adoption and implementation of virtual
28 education plans by a county board during a prolonged state of emergency AFFECTING THE
29 LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM.
30 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
31 July 1, 2026.

